### useId

`useId` generates unique IDs for accessibility attributes. It produces stable, unique strings that are consistent between server and client rendering.

---

### Syntax

```jsx
import { useId } from 'react';

const id = useId();
```

### Accessibility Example

```jsx
function EmailField() {
  const id = useId();

  return (
    <>
      <label htmlFor={id}>Email</label>
      <input id={id} type="email" aria-describedby={`${id}-hint`} />
      <p id={`${id}-hint`}>We'll never share your email.</p>
    </>
  );
}
```

### Multiple Instances

Each component instance gets its own unique ID, preventing collisions:

```jsx
function FormField({ label }) {
  const id = useId();
  return (
    <>
      <label htmlFor={id}>{label}</label>
      <input id={id} />
    </>
  );
}

// Three instances, three unique IDs
<FormField label="Name" />
<FormField label="Email" />
<FormField label="Password" />
```

| Feature | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| SSR compatible | IDs match between server and client |
| Unique per instance | Different IDs for each component instance |
| Stable | IDs don't change between renders |
| Accessibility | Designed for `aria-*` and `htmlFor` attributes |

> **Key Point:** Do not use useId for generating keys in lists. Use IDs from your data. useId is specifically for accessibility attributes that need unique, stable identifiers.

codeExample:
import { useId } from 'react';

function Accordion({ title, children }) {
  const id = useId();
  return (
    <div>
      <button aria-expanded="false" aria-controls={id}>
        {title}
      </button>
      <div id={id} hidden>
        {children}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
